# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: red-hat-linux
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] The first CentOS release in May 2004, numbered as CentOS version 2, was forked from RHEL version 2.1AS.
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] Since version 8, CentOS officially supports the x86-64, ARM64, and POWER8 architectures, and releases up to version 6 also supported the IA-32 architecture.
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] As of December 2015, AltArch releases of CentOS 7 are available for the IA-32 architecture, Power ISA, and for the ARMv7hl and AArch64 variants of the ARM architecture.
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] CentOS 8 was released on 24 September 2019.
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] In December 2020, Red Hat unilaterally terminated CentOS development in favor of CentOS Stream 9, a distribution positioned upstream of RHEL.
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] In March 2021, CloudLinux (makers of CloudLinux OS) released a RHEL derivative called AlmaLinux.
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] Later in May 2021, one of the CentOS founders (Gregory Kurtzer) created the competing Rocky Linux project as a successor to the original mission of CentOS.
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] CentOS originated as a build of **CAOS Linux**, an RPM-based Linux distribution started by Gregory Kurtzer in 2002.
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] Infiscale described its GravityOS as "[including] the small footprint of Caos", indicating a certain level of influence from the discontinued distribution.
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] In June 2006, David Parsley, the primary developer of Tao Linux (another RHEL clone), announced the retirement of Tao Linux and its rolling into CentOS development.
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] Tao users migrated to the CentOS release via yum update.
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] In July 2009, it was reported in an open letter on the CentOS Project web site that one of CentOS's founders, Lance Davis, had disappeared in 2008.
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] Davis had ceased contribution to the project, but continued to hold the registration for the CentOS domain and PayPal account.
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] In August 2009, the CentOS team reportedly made contact with Davis and obtained the centos.info and centos.org domains.
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] In July 2010, CentOS overtook Debian to become the most popular Linux distribution for web servers, with almost 30% of all Linux web servers using it.
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] In January 2014, Red Hat announced that it would sponsor the CentOS Project, "helping to establish a platform well-suited to the needs of open source developers that integrate technologies in and around the operating system".
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] As a result of these changes, ownership of CentOS trademarks was transferred to Red Hat, which now employs most of the CentOS head developers; however, they work as part of Red Hat's Open Source and Standards team, which operates separately from the Red Hat Enterprise Linux team.
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] A new CentOS governing board was also established.
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] On 8 December 2020, the CentOS Project announced that the distribution would be discontinued at the end of 2021 in order to focus on CentOS Stream.
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] The community's response to this announcement was overwhelmingly negative.
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] Soon thereafter, Gregory Kurtzer (one of CentOS's founders) announced a new project to continue the original CentOS focus, which became known as Rocky Linux.
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] CloudLinux created AlmaLinux to provide a community-supported successor to CentOS Linux, aiming for binary-compatibility with the current version of RHEL.
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] A beta version of AlmaLinux was first released on February 1, 2021, and the first stable release of AlmaLinux was published on March 30, 2021.
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] A beta version of Rocky Linux was released on April 30, 2021, and subsequently on June 21, 2021, the stable release of Rocky Linux 8.4 was released.
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] Following CentOS 7's end-of-life in June 2024, several commercial vendors began offering extended security support for organisations unable to migrate immediately.
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] These include TuxCare's Extended Lifecycle Support, CloudLinux's ELS service, and MontaVista's MVShield, which provides continued CVE patching and technical support for CentOS 7.9 through at least 2029.
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] CentOS developers use Red Hat's source code to create a final product very similar to RHEL.
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] Red Hat's branding and logos are changed because Red Hat does not allow them to be redistributed.
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] Technical support is primarily provided by the community via official mailing lists, web forums, and chat rooms.
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] The project is affiliated with Red Hat but aspires to be more public, open, and inclusive.
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] While Red Hat employs most of the CentOS head developers, the CentOS Project itself relies on donations from users and organizational sponsors.
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] CentOS version numbers for releases older than 7.0 have two parts, a major version and a minor version, which correspond to the major version and update set of Red Hat Enterprise Linux (RHEL) used to build a particular CentOS release.
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] For example, CentOS 6.5 is built from the source packages of RHEL 6 update 5 (also known as RHEL version 6.5), which is a so-called "point release" of RHEL 6.
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] Starting with version 7.0, CentOS version numbers also include a third part that indicates the monthstamp of the source code the release is based on.
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] For example, version number 7.0-1406 still maps this CentOS release to the zeroth update set of RHEL 7, while "1406" indicates that the source code this release is based on dates from June 2014.
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] Using the monthstamp allows installation images to be reissued for (as of July 2014) oncoming container and cloud releases, while maintaining a connection to the related base release version.
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] Since mid-2006 and starting with RHEL version 4.4, which is formally known as Red Hat Enterprise Linux 4.0 update 4, Red Hat has adopted a version-naming convention identical to that used by CentOS (for example, RHEL 4.5 or RHEL 6.5).
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] On 10 September 2019 CentOS deferred CentOS 8.1 work for CentOS 7.7 since CentOS 7.x was in production and CentOS 8.x was not in production.
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] Once CentOS 7.7 was released resources moved back to CentOS 8.0.
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] On 24 September 2019 CentOS officially released CentOS version 8.0.
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] Since CentOS was discontinued at the end of 2021, its final release was version 8.5 (2021-11-16).
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] In contrast, its RHEL counterpart continued to version 8.10 (as of 2024-09).
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] According to the Red Hat Enterprise Linux (RHEL) life cycle, CentOS 5, 6 and 7 will be "maintained for up to 10 years" as it is based on RHEL.
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] Previously, CentOS 4 had been supported for seven years.
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] AltArch releases are released by the Alternative Architecture Special Interest Group (AltArch SIG) to support architectures that are not supported by the base CentOS releases.
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] Software Collections (SCL) is a CentOS repository that provides a set of programming languages, database servers, and various related packages.
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] Provided software versions are either more recent than their equivalent versions included in the base CentOS distribution, or are made available as official CentOS packages for the first time.
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] Packages available from the SCL do not replace the default system tools provided with CentOS.
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] Instead, a parallel set of tools is installed in the /opt directory, and can be optionally enabled per application by using supplied scl utility.
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] For example, the default versions of Perl or MySQL remain those provided by the base CentOS installation.
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] Some of the ISO images released by the CentOS Project have no direct upstream equivalents.
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] They are created for specific purposes, such as for providing a live bootable image, or for providing a reduced-size installation medium.
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] In addition to those listed below, there are also AltArch releases, which also have no direct upstream equivalents.
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] LiveCD and LiveDVD images contain a bootable compressed file system, created by a set of custom scripts using a kickstart configuration file.
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] These live images can be also installed to hard disk, thus obtaining a fully functional CentOS installation.
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] The set of packages installed that way on a hard disk can not be adjusted during the installation, as that is a simple transfer of the image existing on CD/DVD, to a hard disk.
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] After booting from hard disk, yum can be used for adding or removing packages.
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] MinimalCD images contain a minimum of packages required for a functional installation, with no compromises in security or network usability.
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] These minimal images use the standard CentOS installer with all of its regular features minus the selection of packages.
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] Yum can be used after the installation is completed to add or remove packages.
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] Special interest groups (SIGs) are organized portions of the CentOS community that open paths for building specialized variants of CentOS, which fulfill specific sets of requirements.
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] SIGs have the freedom to modify and enhance CentOS in various ways, including adding more cutting-edge software, rebuilding existing packages depending on the requirements, providing alternative desktop environments, or making CentOS available on otherwise unsupported architectures.
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] As of December 2015, AltArch releases of CentOS 7 are available for the ARMv7hl and AArch64 variants of the ARM architecture, and plans exist for supporting other variants of the ARM architecture.
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] ARM support is a community effort coordinated through the AltArch SIG.
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] AltArch releases of CentOS 7 are also available for the IA-32 architecture and Power ISA (POWER7 and POWER8 chips).
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] A Live CD version of CentOS is available at *mirror.centos.org*.
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] A bootable Live USB image of CentOS can be created manually or with UNetbootin.
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] CentOS images are also available on Amazon's EC2 cloud, in form of prebuilt and already published Amazon Machine Images (AMIs).
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] The CentOS Project provides several additional repositories that contain software packages not provided by the default `base` and `updates` repositories.
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] Because prior CentOS releases were derived directly from RHEL (RHEL was essentially upstream of CentOS), Stream thus represents a change from prior CentOS releases, being situated between the upstream development in Fedora and the downstream development for RHEL.
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] That said, CentOS Stream 9 and RHEL 9 started from the same codebase and thus CentOS Stream could reasonably be seen as "closer" to RHEL than Fedora.
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] The initial release, CentOS Stream 8, was released on 24 September 2019, at the same time as CentOS 8.
[src:red-hat-linux/centos] As CentOS 8 became unsupported, The CentOS Project provided a simple means of converting from CentOS Linux 8 to CentOS Stream 8.
[src:red-hat-linux/dnf-software] The DNF package manager works similarly to other package managers.
[src:red-hat-linux/dnf-software] Its core usage works very similarly to the Apt Package Manager, such as `install`, `remove`, and `upgrade`.
[src:red-hat-linux/dnf-software] Perceived deficiencies of yum (which DNF is intended to address) include poor performance, high memory usage, and the slowness of its iterative dependency resolution.
[src:red-hat-linux/dnf-software] DNF uses libsolv, an external dependency resolver (developed by openSUSE).
[src:red-hat-linux/dnf-software] DNF was originally written in Python, but in 2016, efforts were under way to port it to C and move most functionality from Python code into the new libdnf library.
[src:red-hat-linux/dnf-software] In 2018, the DNF team announced the decision to move libdnf from C to C++. libdnf is already used by PackageKit, a Linux distribution-agnostic package system abstraction library, even though the library doesn't have most of DNF's features.
[src:red-hat-linux/dnf-software] Since the launch of Fedora Linux 41, DNF5 is the new default packaging tool.
[src:red-hat-linux/dnf-software] This release features new performance enhancements, updated terminal output, and fully integrated modularity.
[src:red-hat-linux/dnf-software] DNF has been the default command-line package manager for Fedora since version 22, which was released in May 2015.
[src:red-hat-linux/dnf-software] The libdnf library is used as a package backend in PackageKit, which offers a graphical user interface (GUI).
[src:red-hat-linux/dnf-software] Later, dnfdragora was developed for Fedora 27 as another alternative graphical front-end of DNF.
[src:red-hat-linux/dnf-software] DNF has also been available as an alternate package manager for Mageia Linux since version 6 and may become the default sometime in the future.
[src:red-hat-linux/dnf-software] In Red Hat Enterprise Linux, and by extension, AlmaLinux and Rocky Linux, yum is an alias for dnf.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] The first version of Red Hat Enterprise Linux to bear the name originally came onto the market as "Red Hat Linux Advanced Server".
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] In 2003, Red Hat rebranded Red Hat Linux Advanced Server to "Red Hat Enterprise Linux AS" and added two more variants, Red Hat Enterprise Linux ES and Red Hat Enterprise Linux WS.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] As Red Hat Enterprise Linux is heavily based on open-source software and its source code is available to the public, it is used as the basis for several third-party derivatives, including the commercial Oracle Linux and the community-supported Rocky Linux and AlmaLinux.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] Prior to June 2023, Red Hat published a sub-set of Red Hat Enterprise Linux's source code to the public in the form of modified build artifacts.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] Today, the complete source code for the major-version branch is available in the form of the CentOS Stream repositories.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] Source code for other release branches remains available to customers in the form of unmodified build artifacts.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] A Red Hat Enterprise Linux Server subscription is available at no cost for development purposes.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] Developers need to register for the Red Hat Developer Program and agree to its license terms.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] The free developer subscription was announced on March 31, 2016, and updated in January 2021 with less restrictive terms.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] There are also "Academic" editions of the Desktop and Server variants.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] They are offered to schools and students, are less expensive, and are provided with Red Hat technical support as an optional extra.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] Web support based on the number of customer contacts can be purchased separately.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] It is often assumed the branding ES, AS, and WS stand for "Entry-level Server", "Advanced Server" and "Work Station", respectively.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] Red Hat had also announced its Red Hat Global Desktop Linux edition "for emerging markets".
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] Originally, Red Hat sold boxed versions of Red Hat Linux directly to consumers and business through phone support.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] The Fedora Project began in 2002 as a set of community supported packages for Red Hat Linux.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] However, the six month release cycle of Red Hat Linux was too disruptive for business users and Red Hat wanted a more reliable revenue stream.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] In 2002 Red Hat began releasing Red Hat Enterprise Linux based on Red Hat Linux, but with a much more conservative release cycle and a subscription based support program.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] A year later, Red Hat discontinued the Red Hat Linux product line, merging it with the Fedora community packages and releasing the resulting Fedora distribution for free.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] Fedora serves as the primary upstream for future major releases of RHEL: RHEL source code repositories are forked off the Fedora repository, and released after a substantial stabilization and quality assurance effort.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] The major-version stable release branch is built and released by the CentOS project under the name CentOS Stream.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] Each minor version of RHEL is a branch of CentOS Stream that gets ongoing bug fixes and security updates.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] For example, CentOS Stream 9 was forked from Fedora in March, 2021 (shortly before the Fedora 34 release) and available on public mirrors in September, 2021.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] In addition, the Fedora project publishes a set of packages for RHEL called the Extra Packages for Enterprise Linux (EPEL).
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] EPEL packages can be expected to work in RHEL, but it is up to willing community members to maintain the packages and back port any upstream changes.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] As such, packages "may come and go" during the ten-year lifespan of the RHEL release and Red Hat support plans do not include resolving issues caused by EPEL packages.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] Red Hat Enterprise Linux is derived from free and open source software.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] Until 2015, Red Hat made the source code to its enterprise distribution publicly available through its FTP website, though the inclusion of Red Hat trademarks prevented direct redistribution of the software.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] In 2015, Red Hat began publishing de-branded source code via git repositories on git.centos.org.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] Several groups used the source code to compile their own derivatives, typically with changes including the removal of any references to Red Hat's trademarks and pointing the update systems to non-Red Hat servers.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] Groups which have undertaken this include AlmaLinux, CentOS, MIRACLE LINUX, Oracle Linux, CloudLinux OS, Rocky Linux, Scientific Linux, StartCom Enterprise Linux, Pie Box Enterprise Linux, X/OS, Lineox, and Bull's XBAS for high-performance computing.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] In 2023, Red Hat replaced the process that published code to git.centos.org in favor of the CentOS Stream git repositories.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] Derivatives of Red Hat Enterprise Linux are free but do not get any commercial support or consulting services from Red Hat and lack software, hardware or security certifications from Red Hat.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] They also do not get access to Red Hat services like Red Hat Network.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] Unusually, Red Hat took steps to obfuscate their changes to the Linux kernel for RHEL 6.0 by not publicly providing the patch files for their changes in the source tarball, and only releasing the finished product in source form.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] Speculation suggested that the move was made to affect Oracle's competing rebuild and support services, which further modifies the distribution.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] This practice however, still complies with the GNU GPL since source code is defined as "[the] preferred form of the work for making modifications to it", and the distribution still complies with this definition.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] Red Hat's CTO Brian Stevens later confirmed the change, stating that certain information (such as patch information) would now only be provided to paying customers to make the Red Hat product more competitive against the growing number of companies offering support for products based on RHEL.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] CentOS developers had no objections to the change since they do not make any changes to the kernel beyond what is provided by Red Hat.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] Their competitor Oracle announced in November 2012 that they were releasing a *RedPatch* service, which allows public view of the RHEL kernel changes, broken down by patch.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] A number of commercial vendors use Red Hat Enterprise Linux as a base for the operating system in their products.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] Two of the best known are the Console Operating System in VMware ESX Server and Oracle Linux.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] Each release is given a codename which is selected by a vote of the developers.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] The codenames don't have a specific pattern (unlike Ubuntu or Debian).
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] Red Hat Enterprise Linux 10 beta was made available in December 2024.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] This release has the codename *Coughlan*.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] Red Hat Enterprise Linux 9 was announced at Red Hat Summit on May 10, 2022, and was officially released on May 17, 2022 (2022-05-17).
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] In this version of the system introduced a Linux Kernel 5.14.0 and Gnome 40.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] RHEL 9 was the first to be based on CentOS Stream, itself based on Fedora Linux, while historically RHEL was based directly on Fedora Linux.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] The first beta for Red Hat Enterprise Linux 9 (*Plow*), based on Fedora Linux 34, was released on November 3, 2021.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] Red Hat Enterprise Linux 9 (*Plow*) was released on May 18, 2022.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] The name *Plow* was the Appalachian Trail nickname for Tim Burke, one of the founders of RHEL and retired leader of RHEL engineering.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] Red Hat Enterprise Linux 8 (*Ootpa*) is based on Fedora 28, upstream Linux kernel 4.18, GCC 8.2, glibc 2.28, systemd 239, GNOME 3.28, and the switch to Wayland.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] The first beta was announced on November 14, 2018.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] Red Hat Enterprise Linux 8 was officially released on May 7, 2019 (2019-05-07).
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] With Release 8 of Red Hat Enterprise Linux, IBM has completed transition of POWER8 and POWER9 servers to little-endian mode.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] The name *Ootpa* was a tribute to Larry Troan.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] His son, Eric Troan was Red Hat's first head engineer and his username was *ewt*, so his father was given the name *ewt's pa*, pronounced *Ootpa*.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] On June 10, 2014 (2014-06-10) Red Hat Enterprise Linux 7 was officially released.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] Red Hat Enterprise Linux 6 was forked from Fedora 10 and contains many backported features from Fedora 11 and Fedora 12.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] Red Hat Enterprise Linux 5 has forked with Fedora Core 6.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] RHEL 4 introduced Linux kernel 2.6 versions and extended attributes on ext2 and ext3 file systems.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] The life cycle of Red Hat Enterprise Linux is at least seven years for versions 3 and 4, and spans at least 10 years for versions 5, 6, 7, 8 and 9.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] The life cycle comprises several phases of varying length with different degrees of support.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] During the first phase ("Production 1"), Red Hat provides full support and updates software and hardware drivers.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] In later phases ("Production 2" and "Production 3"), only security and other important fixes are provided and support for new hardware is gradually reduced.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] This covers a limited number of packages.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] Red Hat only supports major version upgrades from version n to version n+1.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] To maintain a stable application binary interface (ABI), Red Hat does not update the kernel version, but instead backports new features to the same kernel version with which a particular version of RHEL has been released.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] New features are backported throughout the Production 1 phase of the RHEL lifecycle.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] Consequently, RHEL may use a Linux kernel with a dated version number, yet the kernel is up-to-date regarding not only security fixes, but also certain features.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] One specific example is the SO_REUSEPORT socket option which was added to Linux kernel 3.9, and was subsequently backported and became available since RHEL 6.5, which uses version 2.6.32 of the Linux kernel.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] The Extended Update Support (EUS) allows an organization / company to choose when they change to a new minor version.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] For the first 6 months of the EUS channel / yum repo, features may be added, but then the channel is locked down so that only bug and security fixes are patched.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] The organization / company then has 24 months to move to a new EUS branch.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] EUS allows the organization / company to stay on a minor version if required by a third-party application which is only tested with a particular minor version of RHEL, such as Oracle Database, IBM Db2, IBM Cloud Orchestrator, Hortonworks.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] There may also be extra costs associated with using the EUS repos/channels depending on the agreement the organization / company has with Red Hat.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] For more information on what is Included/Excluded from the EUS see.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] In general one can move from z streams to the next version of the z stream.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] Any 7.y.z EUS channel where y is greater than 1.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] The standard base channel for Red Hat Enterprise Linux 7, which is the most recent minor release aka rhel 7Y where y is the latest greatest.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] One can not go back in time, aka 7.5.z to 7.4.z and will NOT be supported.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] Red Hat Enterprise Linux 6 was forked from Fedora 12 and contains many backported features from Fedora 13 and 14.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] Red Hat Enterprise Linux 8 (*Ootpa*) is based on Fedora 28, upstream Linux kernel 4.18, systemd 239, and GNOME 3.28.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] Red Hat Enterprise Linux 8 was officially released on May 7, 2019.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] In addition to normal OS updates, RHEL 8 also maintains application streams to allow for certain applications to be supported and updated independent of the base OS and to match the maintenance stream of the application vendor.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] Each application stream will be supported from two to five years with new versions only available during the Red Hat Enterprise Linux Full Support Phase.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] These apps should be expected to be updated frequently with shorter lifecycles than the base OS packages.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] **Security Enhancements** RHEL 9 includes advanced security measures such as the Integrity Measurement Architecture (IMA), which ensures system integrity.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] It also incorporates OpenSSL 3.0 for updated cryptography and enhanced security policies.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] By default, SSH root password login is disabled to encourage the use of key-based authentication.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] SELinux continues to play a crucial role in enforcing strict security policies.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] **Automation and Management** The integration with Ansible allows for more streamlined automation and configuration management across systems.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] The Cockpit web console has also been improved, offering new features for managing containers, networking, and storage.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] **Cloud and Container Support** RHEL 9 is designed for cloud-native environments, with strong support for containers and hybrid cloud infrastructures.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] It is optimized to work seamlessly with Red Hat OpenShift, a Kubernetes-based platform, and supports containerization through tools like Podman.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] It also includes AppStreams, which provide curated packages for developers, ensuring access to the latest runtimes and frameworks.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] **Networking and Storage** Enhanced NetworkManager features and support for NVMe over Fabrics improve performance and scalability for modern networking and storage configurations.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] RHEL 9 is suitable for a wide range of enterprise applications across industries such as financial services, healthcare, and government.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat-enterprise-linux] RHEL 9 follows Red Hat's 10-year support lifecycle, which includes full support for the first five years, followed by maintenance support for the remaining five years.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] Red Hat has become associated to a large extent with its enterprise operating system Red Hat Enterprise Linux (RHEL).
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] Having grown significantly beyond just Linux, it also includes the OpenShift Container Platform, Ansible Automation Platform, and Red Hat AI.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] Red Hat had acquired the open-source enterprise middleware vendor JBoss.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] Red Hat now offers OpenShift Virtualization, which replaces the long retired product Red Hat Virtualization (RHV), an enterprise virtualization product.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] Red Hat provides operating system platforms, middleware, applications, management products, support, training, and consulting services.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] Red Hat creates, maintains, and contributes to many free software projects.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] It has acquired the codebases of several proprietary software products through corporate mergers and acquisitions, and has released such software under open source licenses.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] As of June 2026, Red Hat is the fourth largest corporate contributor to the Linux kernel after Intel, Meta, and Google.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] On October 28, 2018, IBM announced its intent to acquire Red Hat for $34 billion.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] It now operates as an independent subsidiary.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] Effective January 12, 2026 Red Hat converted (legal process known as "conversion") from a corporation and as Red Hat, Inc. to then be a limited liability company with new formal name Red Hat, LLC.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] In 1993, Bob Young incorporated the ACC Corporation, a catalog business that sold Linux and Unix software accessories.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] In 1994, Marc Ewing created his own Linux distribution, which he named Red Hat Linux (associated with the time Ewing wore a red Cornell University lacrosse hat, given to him by his grandfather, while attending Carnegie Mellon University).
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] Ewing released the software in October, and it became known as the Halloween release.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] Young bought Ewing's business in 1995, and the two merged to become Red Hat Software, with Young serving as chief executive officer (CEO).
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] Red Hat went public on August 11, 1999, achieving—at the time—the eighth-biggest first-day gain in the history of Wall Street.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] Matthew Szulik succeeded Bob Young as CEO in December of that year.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] Bob Young went on to found the online print on demand and self-publishing company, Lulu in 2002.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] On November 15, 1999, Red Hat acquired Cygnus Solutions.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] Cygnus provided commercial support for free software and housed maintainers of GNU software products such as the GNU Debugger and GNU Binutils.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] One of the founders of Cygnus, Michael Tiemann, became the chief technical officer of Red Hat and by 2008 the vice president of open-source affairs.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] Later Red Hat acquired WireSpeed, C2Net, Hell's Kitchen Systems, and Akopia.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] In February 2000, *InfoWorld* awarded Red Hat its fourth consecutive "Operating System Product of the Year" award for Red Hat Linux 6.1.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] Red Hat acquired Planning Technologies, Inc. in 2001 and AOL's iPlanet directory and certificate-server software in 2004.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] Red Hat moved its headquarters from Durham to North Carolina State University's Centennial Campus in Raleigh, North Carolina in February 2002.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] In the following month Red Hat introduced Red Hat Linux Advanced Server, later renamed Red Hat Enterprise Linux (RHEL).
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] Dell, IBM, HP and Oracle Corporation announced their support of the platform.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] In December 2005, *CIO Insight* magazine conducted its annual "Vendor Value Survey", in which Red Hat ranked #1 in value for the second year in a row.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] Red Hat stock became part of the NASDAQ-100 on December 19, 2005.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] Red Hat acquired open-source middleware provider JBoss on June 5, 2006, and JBoss became a division of Red Hat.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] On September 18, 2006, Red Hat released the Red Hat Application Stack, which integrated the JBoss technology and which was certified by other well-known software vendors.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] On December 12, 2006, Red Hat stock moved from trading on NASDAQ (RHAT) to the New York Stock Exchange (RHT).
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] In 2007 Red Hat acquired MetaMatrix and made an agreement with Exadel to distribute its software.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] On March 15, 2007, Red Hat released Red Hat Enterprise Linux 5, and in June acquired Mobicents.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] On March 13, 2008, Red Hat acquired Amentra, a provider of systems integration services for service-oriented architecture, business process management, systems development, and enterprise data services.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] On July 27, 2009, Red Hat replaced CIT Group in Standard and Poor's 500 stock index, a diversified index of 500 leading companies of the U.S. economy.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] This was reported as a major milestone for Linux.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] On December 15, 2009, it was reported that Red Hat would pay US$8.8 million to settle a class action lawsuit related to the restatement of financial results from July 2004.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] District Court for the Eastern District of North Carolina.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] Red Hat reached the proposed settlement agreement and recorded a one-time charge of US$8.8 million for the quarter that ended Nov.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] On January 10, 2011, Red Hat announced that it would expand its headquarters in two phases, adding 540 employees to the Raleigh operation, and investing over US$109 million.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] The state of North Carolina is offering up to US$15 million in incentives.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] The second phase involves "expansion into new technologies such as software virtualization and technology cloud offerings".
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] On August 25, 2011, Red Hat announced it would move about 600 employees from the N.C.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] State Centennial Campus to the Two Progress Plaza building.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] A ribbon cutting ceremony was held on June 24, 2013, in the re-branded Red Hat Headquarters.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] In 2012, Red Hat became the first one-billion dollar open-source company, reaching US$1.13 billion in annual revenue during its fiscal year.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] Red Hat passed the $2 billion benchmark in 2015.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] As of February 2018 the company's annual revenue was nearly $3 billion.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] On October 16, 2015, Red Hat announced its acquisition of IT automation startup Ansible, rumored for an estimated US$100 million.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] In June 2017, Red Hat announced Red Hat Hyperconverged Infrastructure (RHHI) 1.0 software product.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] On October 28, 2018, IBM announced its intent to acquire Red Hat for US$34 billion, in one of its largest-ever acquisitions.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] The company will operate out of IBM's Hybrid Cloud division.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] Microsoft, Amazon, and Google reportedly also considered buying Red Hat.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] Six months later, on May 3, 2019, the US Department of Justice concluded its review of IBM's proposed Red Hat acquisition, and according to Steven J.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] Vaughan-Nichols "essentially approved the IBM/Red Hat deal".
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] The acquisition was closed on July 9, 2019.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] Red Hat is the primary sponsor of the Fedora Project, a community-supported free software project that aims to promote the rapid progress of free and open-source software and content.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] Red Hat operates on a business model based on open-source software, development within a community, professional quality assurance, and subscription-based customer support.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] They produce open-source code so that more programmers can make adaptations and improvements.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] Red Hat sells subscriptions for the support, training, and integration services that help customers in using their open-source software products.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] Customers pay one set price for unlimited access to services such as Red Hat Network and up to 24/7 support.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] In September 2014, however, CEO Jim Whitehurst announced that Red Hat was "in the midst of a major shift from client-server to cloud-mobile".
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] Rich Bynum, a member of Red Hat's legal team, attributes Linux's success and rapid development partially to open-source business models, including Red Hat's.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] Red Hat's links to branches of Israel's military and statements of support for Israeli associates has also led to some controversy and calls for boycott during the ongoing conflict in Gaza.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] Air Force and US Department of Defense supplier, working closely with Lockheed Martin on warfare-related AI capabilities.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] In 2026, a brochure titled "Compress the kill cycle with Red Hat Device Edge" surfaced, but it was promptly removed from Red Hat websites.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] Red Hat engineers worked with the One Laptop per Child initiative (a non-profit organization established by members of the MIT Media Lab) to design and produce an inexpensive laptop and try to provide every child in the world with access to open communication, open knowledge, and open learning.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] The XO-4 laptop, the last machine the project produced (in 2012), runs a slimmed-down version of Fedora 17 as its operating system.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] Avi Kivity began the development of KVM in mid-2006 at Qumranet, a technology startup company that was acquired by Red Hat in 2008.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] Red Hat is the largest contributor to the GNOME desktop environment.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] It has several employees working full-time on Evolution, the official personal information manager for GNOME.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] Init system and system/service manager for Linux systems.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] Network-capable sound server program distributed via the freedesktop.org project.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] Dogtail, an open-source automated graphical user interface (GUI) test framework initially developed by Red Hat, consists of free software released under the GNU General Public License (GPL) and is written in Python.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] It allows developers to build and test their applications.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] Red Hat announced the release of Dogtail at the 2006 Red Hat Summit.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] Red Hat MRG is a clustering product intended for integrated high-performance computing (HPC).
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] The acronym MRG stands for "Messaging Realtime Grid".
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] As of 2011, Red Hat works with the Condor High-Throughput Computing System community and also provides support for the software.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] The Tuna performance-monitoring tool runs in the MRG environment.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] Red Hat produced the online publication Opensource.com since January 20, 2010.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] The site highlights ways open-source principles apply in domains other than software development.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] The site tracks the application of open-source philosophy to business, education, government, law, health, and life.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] The company originally produced a newsletter called Under the Brim.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] Wide Open magazine first appeared in March 2004, as a means for Red Hat to share technical content with subscribers regularly.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] The Under the Brim newsletter and Wide Open magazine merged in November 2004, to become *Red Hat Magazine*.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] In January 2010, *Red Hat Magazine* became Opensource.com.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] In April 2023 Red Hat went through company layoffs and laid off the team maintaining Opensource.com.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] In 2007, Red Hat announced that it had reached an agreement with some free software and open-source (FOSS) companies that allowed it to make a distribution portal called Red Hat Exchange, reselling FOSS software with the original branding intact.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] However, by 2010, Red Hat had abandoned the Exchange program to focus their efforts more on their Open Source Channel Alliance which began in April 2009.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] Red Hat build of Keycloak (formerly known as Red Hat Single Sign-On) is a software product to allow single sign-on with Identity Management and Access Management aimed at modern applications and services.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] It is based on the open-source project Keycloak, which acts as an upstream project.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] Red Hat Subscription Management (RHSM) combines content delivery with subscription management.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] Red Hat is the largest contributor to the Ceph Storage SDS project : Block, File & Object Storage which runs on industry-standard x86 servers and Ethernet IP as well as ARM, InfiniBand, and other technologies.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] Ceph aims primarily for completely distributed operation without a single point of failure, scalable to the exabyte level.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] Ceph replicates data and makes it fault-tolerant, using commodity hardware and requiring no specific hardware support.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] Ceph's system offers disaster recovery and data redundancy through techniques such as replication, erasure coding, snapshots and storage cloning.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] As a result of its design, the system is both self-healing and self-managing, aiming to minimize administration time and other costs.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] In this way, administrators have a single, consolidated system that avoids silos and collects the storage within a common management framework.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] Ceph consolidates several storage use cases and improves resource utilization.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] It also lets an organization deploy servers where needed.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] Red Hat operates OpenShift, a cloud computing platform as a service, supporting applications written in Node.js, PHP, Perl, Python, Ruby, JavaEE and more.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] On July 31, 2018, Red Hat announced the release of Istio 1.0, a microservices management program used in tandem with the Kubernetes platform.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] The software purports to provide "traffic management, service identity and security, policy enforcement and telemetry" services in order to streamline Kubernetes use under the various Fedora-based operating systems.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] Red Hat's Brian Redbeard Harring described Istio as "aiming to be a control plane, similar to the Kubernetes control plane, for configuring a series of proxy servers that get injected between application components".
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] Also Red Hat is the second largest contributor to Kubernetes code itself, after Google.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] Red Hat markets a version of OpenStack which helps manage a data center in the manner of cloud computing.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] Red Hat CloudForms provides management of virtual machines, instances and containers based on VMware vSphere, Red Hat Virtualization, Microsoft Hyper-V, OpenStack, Amazon EC2, Google Cloud Platform, Microsoft Azure, and Red Hat OpenShift.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] CloudForms is based on the ManageIQ project that Red Hat open sourced.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] Code in ManageIQ is from the over US$100 million acquisition of ManageIQ in 2012.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] Container Linux (formerly CoreOS Linux) is a discontinued open-source lightweight operating system based on the Linux kernel and designed for providing infrastructure to clustered deployments.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] As an operating system, Container Linux provided only the minimal functionality required for deploying applications inside software containers, together with built-in mechanisms for service discovery and configuration sharing.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] Red Hat contributed, with several software developers, to LibreOffice, a free and open-source office suite.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] However, in 2023, Red Hat announced they were not going to include LibreOffice in RHEL 10, citing the ability to download LibreOffice from Flatpak on RHEL desktops.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] Red Hat also organises "Open Source Day" events where multiple partners show their open-source technologies.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] Red Hat was one of the largest contributors to the X Window System.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] Started in 2008, by Red Hat developer Kristian Høgsberg, with the aim of replacing the X Windows System.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] Over and above Red Hat's major products and acquisitions, Red Hat programmers have produced software programming-tools and utilities to supplement standard Unix and Linux software.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] Some of these Red Hat "products" have found their way from specifically Red Hat operating environments via open-source channels to a wider community.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] The Red Hat website lists the organization's major involvements in free and open-source software projects.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] Red Hat Czech s.r.o. is a research and development arm of Red Hat, based in Brno, Czech Republic.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] The subsidiary was formed in 2006 and has 1,180 employees (2019).
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] Red Hat chose to enter the Czech Republic in 2006 over other locations due to the country's embrace of open-source.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] The subsidiary expanded in 2017 to a second location in the Brno Technology Park to accommodate an additional 350 employees.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] In 2016, Red Hat Czech reported revenue of CZK 1,002 million (FY 2016), and net income of CZK 123 million (FY 2016), with assets of CZK 420 million (FY 2016)|CZK 325 million (FY 2015).
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] The group was named the "Most progressive employer of the year" in the Czech Republic in 2010, and the "Best Employer in the Czech Republic" for large scale companies in 2011 by Aon.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] In 2000, Red Hat created the subsidiary **Red Hat India** to deliver Red Hat software, support, and services to Indian customers.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] As of today (2025 December) 1800 employees work for Red Hat India.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] Colin Tenwick, former vice president and general manager of Red Hat EMEA, said Red Hat India was opened "in response to the rapid adoption of Red Hat Linux in the subcontinent.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] Demand for open-source solutions from the Indian markets is rising and Red Hat wants to play a major role in this region." Red Hat India has worked with local companies to enable the adoption of open-source technology in both government and education.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] In 2006, Red Hat India had a distribution network of more than 70 channel partners spanning 27 cities across India.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] Red Hat India's channel partners included MarkCraft Solutions, Ashtech Infotech Pvt Ltd., Efensys Technologies, Embee Software, Allied Digital Services, and Softcell Technologies.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] Distributors include Integra Micro Systems and Ingram Micro.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] Red Hat's first major acquisition involved Delix Computer GmbH-Linux Div, the Linux-based operating-system division of Delix Computer, a German computer company, on July 30, 1999.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] Red Hat acquired Cygnus Solutions, a company that provided commercial support for free software, on January 11, 2000 – it was the company's largest acquisition, for US$674 million.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] Michael Tiemann, co-founder of Cygnus, served as the chief technical officer of Red Hat after the acquisition.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] Red Hat made the most acquisitions in 2000 with five: Cygnus Solutions, Bluecurve, Wirespeed Communications, Hell's Kitchen Systems, and C2Net.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] On June 5, 2006, Red Hat acquired open-source middleware provider JBoss for US$420 million and integrated it as its own division of Red Hat.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] On December 14, 1998, Red Hat made its first divestment, when Intel and Netscape acquired undisclosed minority stakes in the company.
[src:red-hat-linux/red-hat] The next year, on March 9, 1999, Compaq, IBM, Dell and Novell each acquired undisclosed minority stakes in Red Hat.
