[src:red-hat-linux/rpm-package-manager] Although it was created for use in Red Hat Linux, RPM is now used in many Linux distributions such as PCLinuxOS, Fedora Linux, AlmaLinux, CentOS, openSUSE, OpenMandriva and Oracle Linux.
[src:red-hat-linux/rpm-package-manager] It has also been ported to some other operating systems, such as Novell NetWare (as of version 6.5 SP3), IBM's AIX (as of version 4), IBM i, and ArcaOS.
[src:red-hat-linux/rpm-package-manager] An RPM package can contain an arbitrary set of files.
[src:red-hat-linux/rpm-package-manager] Most RPM files are "binary RPMs" (or BRPMs) containing the compiled version of some software.
[src:red-hat-linux/rpm-package-manager] There are also "source RPMs" (or SRPMs) containing the source code used to build a binary package.
[src:red-hat-linux/rpm-package-manager] These have an appropriate tag in the file header that distinguishes them from normal (B)RPMs, causing them to be extracted to /usr/src on installation.
[src:red-hat-linux/rpm-package-manager] SRPMs customarily carry the file extension ".src.rpm" (.spm on file systems limited to 3 extension characters, e.g. old DOS FAT).
[src:red-hat-linux/rpm-package-manager] RPM was originally written in 1997 by Erik Troan and Marc Ewing, based on `pms`, `rpp`, and `pm` experiences.
[src:red-hat-linux/rpm-package-manager] `pm` was written by Rik Faith and Doug Hoffman in May 1995 for Red Hat Software, its design and implementations were influenced greatly by `pms`, a package management system by Faith and Kevin Martin in the fall of 1993 for the Bogus Linux Distribution.
[src:red-hat-linux/rpm-package-manager] `pm` preserves the "Pristine Sources + patches" paradigm of `pms`, while adding features and eliminating arbitrary limitations present in the implementation.
[src:red-hat-linux/rpm-package-manager] `pm` provides greatly enhanced database support for tracking and verifying installed packages.
[src:red-hat-linux/rpm-package-manager] Packages may come from within a particular distribution (for example Red Hat Enterprise Linux) or be built for it by other parties (for example RPM Fusion for Fedora Linux).
[src:red-hat-linux/rpm-package-manager] Circular dependencies among mutually dependent RPMs (so-called "dependency hell") can be problematic; in such cases a single installation command needs to specify all the relevant packages.
[src:red-hat-linux/rpm-package-manager] RPMs are often collected centrally in one or more repositories on the internet.
[src:red-hat-linux/rpm-package-manager] A site often has its own RPM repositories which may either act as local mirrors of such internet repositories or be locally maintained collections of useful RPMs.
[src:red-hat-linux/rpm-package-manager] Several front-ends to RPM ease the process of obtaining and installing RPMs from repositories and help in resolving their dependencies.
[src:red-hat-linux/rpm-package-manager] Working behind the scenes of the package manager is the RPM database, stored in `/var/lib/rpm`.
[src:red-hat-linux/rpm-package-manager] It consists of a single database (`Packages`) containing all of the meta information of the installed RPMs.
[src:red-hat-linux/rpm-package-manager] Multiple databases are created for indexing purposes, replicating data to speed up queries.
[src:red-hat-linux/rpm-package-manager] The database is used to keep track of all files that are changed and created when a user (using RPM) installs a package, thus enabling the user (via RPM) to reverse the changes and remove the package later.
[src:red-hat-linux/rpm-package-manager] If the database gets corrupted (which is possible if the RPM client is killed), the index databases can be recreated with the `rpm --rebuilddb` command.
[src:red-hat-linux/rpm-package-manager] Whilst the RPM format is the same across different Linux distributions, the detailed conventions and guidelines may vary across them.
[src:red-hat-linux/rpm-package-manager] RPMs with the `noarch.rpm` extension do not depend on a particular CPU architecture.
[src:red-hat-linux/rpm-package-manager] For example, these RPMs may contain graphics and text for other programs to use.
[src:red-hat-linux/rpm-package-manager] They may also contain shell scripts or programs written in other interpreted programming languages such as Python.
[src:red-hat-linux/rpm-package-manager] The package label fields do not need to match the filename.
[src:red-hat-linux/rpm-package-manager] Libraries are distributed in two separate packages for each version.
[src:red-hat-linux/rpm-package-manager] One contains the precompiled code for use at run-time, while the second one contains the related development files such as headers, etc.
[src:red-hat-linux/rpm-package-manager] Those packages have "-devel" appended to their name field.
[src:red-hat-linux/rpm-package-manager] The system administrator should ensure that the versions of the binary and development packages match.
[src:red-hat-linux/rpm-package-manager] The "Recipe" for creating an RPM package is a spec file.
[src:red-hat-linux/rpm-package-manager] Spec files end in the ".spec" suffix and contain the package name, version, RPM revision number, steps to build, install, and clean a package, and a changelog.
[src:red-hat-linux/rpm-package-manager] Multiple packages can be built from a single RPM spec file, if desired.
[src:red-hat-linux/rpm-package-manager] RPM packages are created from RPM spec files using the rpmbuild tool.
[src:red-hat-linux/rpm-package-manager] Spec files are usually distributed within SRPM files, which contain the spec file packaged along with the source code.
[src:red-hat-linux/rpm-package-manager] A typical RPM is pre-compiled software ready for direct installation.
[src:red-hat-linux/rpm-package-manager] The corresponding source code can also be distributed.
[src:red-hat-linux/rpm-package-manager] This is done in an SRPM, which also includes the "SPEC" file describing the software and how it is built.
[src:red-hat-linux/rpm-package-manager] The SRPM also allows the user to compile, and perhaps modify, the code itself.
[src:red-hat-linux/rpm-package-manager] A software package could contain only platform independent scripts.
[src:red-hat-linux/rpm-package-manager] In such a case, the developer could provide only an SRPM, which is still an installable RPM.
[src:red-hat-linux/rpm-package-manager] It contains "SPEC" file and optionally patches, but does not include sources (usually because of license).
[src:red-hat-linux/rpm-package-manager] As of June 2010, there are two versions of RPM in development: one led by the Fedora Project and Red Hat, and the other by a separate group led by a previous maintainer of RPM, a former employee of Red Hat.
[src:red-hat-linux/rpm-package-manager] The *rpm.org* community's first major code revision was in July 2007; version 4.8 was released in January 2010, version 4.9 in March 2011, 4.10 in May 2012, 4.11 in January 2013, 4.12 in September 2014 and 4.13 in July 2015.
[src:red-hat-linux/rpm-package-manager] This version is used by distributions such as Fedora Linux, Red Hat Enterprise Linux and derivatives, openSUSE, SUSE Linux Enterprise, Unity Linux, Mageia, OpenEmbedded, Tizen and OpenMandriva Lx (formerly Mandriva).
[src:red-hat-linux/rpm-package-manager] Jeff Johnson, the RPM maintainer since 1999, continued development efforts together with participants from several other distributions.
[src:red-hat-linux/rpm-package-manager] This version was used by distributions such as Wind River Linux (until Wind River Linux 10), Rosa Linux, and OpenMandriva Lx (former Mandriva Linux which switched to rpm5 in 2011) and also by the OpenPKG project which provides packages for other common UNIX-platforms.
[src:red-hat-linux/rpm-package-manager] OpenMandriva Lx has switched back to rpm.org for 4.0 release.
[src:red-hat-linux/rpm-package-manager] OpenEmbedded, the last major user of RPM5, switched back to rpm.org due to issues in RPM5.
[src:red-hat-linux/yum-software] The **Yellowdog Updater Modified** (**YUM**) is a free and open-source command-line package-management utility for computers running the Linux operating system using the RPM Package Manager.
[src:red-hat-linux/yum-software] Though YUM has a command-line interface, several other tools provide graphical user interfaces to YUM functionality.
[src:red-hat-linux/yum-software] YUM allows for automatic updates and package and dependency management on RPM-based distributions.
[src:red-hat-linux/yum-software] Like the Advanced Package Tool (APT) from Debian, YUM works with software repositories (collections of packages), which can be accessed locally or over a network connection.
[src:red-hat-linux/yum-software] YUM is implemented as libraries in the Python programming language, with a small set of programs that provide a command-line interface.
[src:red-hat-linux/yum-software] GUI-based wrappers such as YUM Extender (yumex) also exist, and has been adopted for Fedora Linux until version 22.
[src:red-hat-linux/yum-software] A rewrite of YUM named DNF replaced YUM as the default package manager in Fedora 22 (in 2015).
[src:red-hat-linux/yum-software] This was required due to Fedora's transition from Python 2 to Python 3, which is not supported by YUM.
[src:red-hat-linux/yum-software] DNF also improves on YUM in several ways - improved performance, better resolution of dependency conflicts, and easier integration with other software applications.
[src:red-hat-linux/yum-software] The original package manager, Yellowdog UPdater (YUP) was developed in 1999–2001 by Dan Burcaw, Bryan Stillwell, Stephen Edie, and Troy Bengegerdes at Terra Soft Solutions (under the leadership of then CEO Kai Staats) as a back-end engine for a graphical installer of Yellow Dog Linux.
[src:red-hat-linux/yum-software] As a full rewrite of YUP, YUM evolved primarily to update and manage Red Hat Linux systems used at the Duke University Department of Physics by Seth Vidal and Michael Stenner.
[src:red-hat-linux/yum-software] Vidal continued to contribute to YUM until his death in a Durham, North Carolina bicycle accident on 8 July 2013.
[src:red-hat-linux/yum-software] Brown at Duke published documentation for YUM.
[src:red-hat-linux/yum-software] Subsequent adopters included Fedora, Rocky Linux, AlmaLinux, CentOS, and many other RPM-based Linux distributions, including Yellow Dog Linux itself, where YUM replaced the original YUP utility — last updated on SourceForge in 2001.
[src:red-hat-linux/yum-software] By 2005, it was estimated to be in use on over half of the Linux market, and by 2007 YUM was considered the "tool of choice" for RPM-based Linux distributions.
[src:red-hat-linux/yum-software] YUM aimed to address both the perceived deficiencies in the old APT-RPM, and restrictions of the Red Hat up2date package management tool.
[src:red-hat-linux/yum-software] YUM superseded up2date in Red Hat Enterprise Linux 5 and later.
[src:red-hat-linux/yum-software] Some authors refer to YUM as the Yellowdog Update Manager, or suggest that "Your Update Manager" would be more appropriate.
[src:red-hat-linux/yum-software] A basic knowledge of YUM is often included as a requirement for Linux system-administrator certification.
[src:red-hat-linux/yum-software] The GNU General Public License of YUM allows the free and open-source software to be freely distributed and modified without any royalty, if other terms of the license are honored.
[src:red-hat-linux/yum-software] While yum was originally created for Linux, it has been ported to a number of other operating systems including AIX, IBM i, and ArcaOS.
[src:red-hat-linux/yum-software] The 2.x versions of YUM feature an additional interface for programming extensions in Python that allows the behavior of YUM to be altered.
[src:red-hat-linux/yum-software] Certain plug-ins are installed by default.
[src:red-hat-linux/yum-software] A commonly installed package `yum-utils`, contains commands which use the YUM API, and many plugins.
[src:red-hat-linux/yum-software] Graphical user interfaces, known as "front-ends", allow easier use of YUM.
[src:red-hat-linux/yum-software] PackageKit and Yum Extender (yumex) are two examples.
[src:red-hat-linux/yum-software] Yum Extender was deprecated for a while when Fedora migrated to DNF, but it was rewritten in Python 3 and Gtk 3 and has been in progress for development.
[src:red-hat-linux/yum-software] This brand-new Yum Extender is available for Fedora 34 or newer.
[src:red-hat-linux/yum-software] Information about packages (as opposed to the packages themselves) is known as metadata.
[src:red-hat-linux/yum-software] These metadata are combined with information in each package to determine (and resolve, if possible) dependencies among the packages.
[src:red-hat-linux/yum-software] The hope is to avoid a situation known as dependency hell.
[src:red-hat-linux/yum-software] A separate tool, `createrepo`, sets up YUM software repositories, generating the necessary metadata in a standard XML format (and the SQLite metadata if given the -d option).
[src:red-hat-linux/yum-software] The `mrepo` tool (formerly known as Yam) can help in the creation and maintenance of repositories.
[src:red-hat-linux/yum-software] YUM's XML repository, built with input from many other developers, quickly became the standard for RPM-based repositories.
[src:red-hat-linux/yum-software] Besides the distributions that use YUM directly, SUSE Linux 10.1 added support for YUM repositories in YaST, and the Open Build Service repositories use the YUM XML repository format metadata.
[src:red-hat-linux/yum-software] YUM automatically synchronizes the remote meta data to the local client, with other tools opting to synchronize only when requested by the user.
[src:red-hat-linux/yum-software] Having automatic synchronization means that YUM cannot fail due to the user failing to run a command at the correct interval.
